    <stitle>International&#174; MaxxForce&#8482; 7 Engine Service Manual - Power Cylinders - Cleaning and Inspection -
        Pistons
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s14.3.2" svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="4">
        <title>Pistons</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect pistons for scuffed or scored skirts, cracked or worn ring lands, and cracked or
                scuffed pin bores. Replace damaged pistons.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Top compression ring groove is a keystone design which requires measurement over gauge pins to
                    determine ring groove wear.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check top compression ring groove for wear.</para>
            <figure id="f3450014008" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd04/d0420.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Top compression ring groove</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Piston gauge pins (2.0828 mm [0.082 in]) ZTSE4513</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">piston gauge pins (2.0828 mm [0.082 in]) ZTSE4513
                </hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t3"/>
                in top compression ring groove. Piston gauge pins must be parallel.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">3 - 4 inch micrometer</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t3"/>
                to measure diameter over piston gauge pins.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If measurement over gauge pin is not within
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">specifications</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t1"/>, excessive piston groove wear exists. Replace piston.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014009" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/d0403.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Second and third ring groove clearance check (intermediate ring shown)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Intermediate ring groove</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check side clearance of intermediate ring groove as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place outer edge of new ring in its respective ring groove.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Roll ring entirely around piston in its respective groove. Make sure ring is able to
                    move freely in its groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a
                    <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">feeler gauge</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="s14.t3"/>
                    to check
                    <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">side clearance of each ring in its respective
                        groove
                    </hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="s14.t1"/>. Excessive side clearance indicates ring groove wear and requires piston
                    replacement.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check side clearance of oil control ring groove as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Place outer edge of new ring in oil control ring groove.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Roll ring entirely around piston in its respective groove. Make sure ring moves freely
                    in groove.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use a
                    <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">feeler gauge</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="s14.t3"/>
                    to check
                    <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">side clearance of oil control ring in its
                        respective groove
                    </hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="s14.t1"/>. Excessive side clearance indicates ring groove wear and requires piston
                    replacement.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014010" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/d0416.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston skirt diameter</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston skirt</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">3 - 4 inch micrometer</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">When considering piston replacement, check cylinder bore out-of-round specifications. See
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_311.xml" xrefid="s15.3.1.2.ref1">Crankcase Inspection</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s15.3.1.2.ref1"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If not within
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">specification</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t1"/>, cylinder boring may be required. Bore reconditioning requires oversize service
                pistons. Verify piston size by measuring skirt diameter under conditions indicated in
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">specifications</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t1"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>In addition to standard size service piston, the following oversize pistons are available.</para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>0.254 mm (0.010 in)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>0.508 mm (0.020 in)</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>0.762 mm (0.030 in)</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If cylinder walls have minor surface damage, but are otherwise within specification
                (out-of-round), it may be possible to remove such damage by honing. If cylinder bore is suitable for use
                without reconditioning, deglaze bore using a
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">glaze breaker brush</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t3"/>, then reassemble.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>See
                    <hotlnk document="eges3451_311.xml" xrefid="s15.3.1.3.ref1">Cylinder Deglazing</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="s15.3.1.3.ref1"/>
                    for correct procedure.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f3450014011" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figM04/M04104.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston skirt clearance check in cylinder bore</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Piston</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Crankcase</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_297.xml" xrefid="s14.t1">piston skirt clearance in cylinder bore</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t1"/>. Correct as required.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
